Demonstrating Regressors Using Boston Housing Dataset¶

By Ciaran Lowell¶

This project showcases multiple different regression methods and compares the accuracy of those methods. Note that these regressors will be using arbitrarily chosen hyperparameters and have not necessarily been tuned for best possible performance.

I had planned to show model residuals using the Yellowbrick library, but it did not cooperate well with some of the Regressor libraries, so I instead used a simple pyplot function that I coded.

Methods Compared¶

  1. Linear Regression
  2. Neural Network
  3. XGBoost
  4. Support Vector Regression
  5. Kernel Weighted Local Regression
    • Gaussian Kernel
    • Aitchison Aitken Kernel

Data¶

This project used the Boston Housing Dataset. Specifically, I used the "Median Number of Rooms" variable to predict the house price. The observations correspond to the "Median Number of Rooms" and "Median House Price" within neighborhoods of Boston.

The dataset is small and represents only 506 observations. The small size of the dataset resulted in overfitting issues with some of the models. In the future, KFold Cross-Validation would likely need to be used to reduce overfitting problems.

Data was be split into a Train set of 380 observations and a Test set of 126 observations. The train and test sets were reshaped to be more compatible with the regressors and graphing functions.

The dataset appears to have been "censored" at $50,000, with an unusual number of datapoints recording that exact price.

def graphResiduals(modelName, X_test_input, y_test_input, y_pred_input):
  y_hat = abs(y_pred_input - y_test_input)
  plt.scatter(X_test_input,y_hat, color  = 'red')
  plt.title('%s Error Residuals' % (modelName))
  plt.xlabel("Median Number of Rooms")
  plt.ylabel("Residual Error (in Thousands of Dollars)")
  plt.show()
In [96]:
def graphResults(modelName, X_input, y_input,  X_test_input, y_pred_input):
  plt.scatter(X_input, y_input)
  plt.plot(X_test_input, y_pred_input, color='red', label = modelName)
  plt.title('%s- # of Rooms vs. Price' % (modelName))
  plt.xlabel("Median Number of Rooms")
  plt.ylabel("House Price (units = $1000)")
  plt.legend()
  plt.show()
In [164]:
def printMetrics(modelName, y_test_input, y_pred_input):
  print("*%s* Metrics: " % (modelName))
  print("Mean absolute error = $", round(skm.mean_absolute_error(y_test_input, y_pred_input)*1000, 2)) 
  print("Mean squared error = $", round(skm.mean_squared_error(y_test_input, y_pred_input)*1000, 2)) 
  print("Median absolute error = $", round(skm.median_absolute_error(y_test_input, y_pred_input)*1000, 2)) 
  print("R2 score =", round(skm.r2_score(y_test_input, y_pred_input), 2))

Linear Regression¶

A simple linear regression is fit to the data using SKLearn's Linear Regression package. The regressor is not fit to intercept the origin.

The linear regressor's residual plot somewhat fits the normal distribution, but shows greater errors past 7 rooms.

In [136]:

linear = linear_regressor.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_lr = linear.predict(dat_test[:,0].reshape((dat_test[:,0].shape[0]), 1))
In [137]:

XGBoost¶

XGBoost stands for "Extreme Gradient Boosting." The model creates a forest of decision trees.

XGBoost is an extremely powerful algorithm that utilizes boosted decision trees to quickly make predictions. Unfortunately, it also is prone to overfitting. The XGBoost model created by the Test dataset seems to be overfit. I adjusted the input parameters and reduced some of the overfitting, but the model still appears overfit on the data.

The residual plot follows a normal distribution.

In [139]:

xg_regressor.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_xgb = xg_regressor.predict(X_test_reshape).reshape(X_test_reshape.shape[0], 1)

Support Vector Regression¶

Support Vector Regression uses Support Vector Machines to find optimal hyperplanes for variable prediction. This model has been fit using the default hyperparameters from the SKlearn Support Vector Regression toolkit.

The graph shows SVR developing a sigmoid-esque shape for predicting this data. The residuals appear to be homoscedastic and follow a normal distribution.

In [142]:

SupportVR.fit(X_train,y_train)
y_pred_SVR = SupportVR.predict(X_test_reshape).reshape(X_test_reshape.shape[0], 1)

Neural Net¶

This Neural Net is a simple 5-layer model that uses Dense layers with a relu activation function. The net has been optimized to reduce Mean Squared Error using the Adam optimizer, and has an Early Stopping parameter to prevent overfitting and excessive runtime.

The Neural Net's line of best fit takes the form of 3 different piecewise linear functions.

The Residuals appear homoscedastic.

In [145]:
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(128, activation="relu", input_dim=1))
model.add(Dense(64, activation = "relu"))
model.add(Dense(32, activation="relu"))
model.add(Dense(8, activation="relu"))
model.add(Dense(1, activation="linear"))

model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer=Adam(lr=1e-3, decay=1e-3 / 200))

es = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min', verbose=1, patience=1000)

history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_split=0.3, epochs=1000, batch_size=100, verbose=0, callbacks=[es])
In [146]:
# Calculate predictions
y_pred_nn = model.predict(X_test_reshape)

Weighted Kernel Regressions¶

The StatsModels Kernel Regression package provides the ability to implment Weighted Kernel Regressions while specifying the type of kernel to use.

Illustrated below are usages of the Gaussian kernel and the Aitchison Aitken Kernel.

Gaussian Kernel¶

The Gaussian kernel

The line of fit for this model looks similar to the Support Vector line. The residuals are homoscedastic and normally distributed.

In [149]:
from statsmodels.nonparametric.kernel_regression import KernelReg

model_KernRegGauss = KernelReg(endog=y_train,exog=X_train,var_type='c', ckertype='gaussian')
In [150]:
yhat_smG, y_stdG = model_KernRegGauss.fit(X_test_reshape)
In [151]:
graphResults("StatsModels Gaussian Kernel Regression", X, y, X_test_reshape, yhat_smG)
In [152]:
yhat_smG = yhat_smG.reshape((dat_test[:,0].shape[0]), 1)
graphResiduals("StatsModels Gaussian Kernel Regression", X_test_reshape, y_test_reshape, yhat_smG)

Aitchson Aitken Kernel Regression¶

This application incorporates the kernel suggested by Aitchson and Aitken in their 1970 research paper.

The kernel's line of fit is mostly a linear model with some deviations in the areas with the most dense data points. These deviations suggest overfitting and that the model hyperparameters should be better tuned in the future.

The residuals appear homoscedastic and normally distributed.

In [153]:

Overall, the Neural Net has the best R2 score, while the Support Vector regression has the lowest Median absolute error.

Most of the models have an R2 close to .5, which indicates they are not performing much better than a linear model. More hyperparameter tuning would be needed in the future to produce more accurate models that have lower errors.
